  "prompt": "What are credits for in engineering?",
  "response": "In engineering, credits are a way to measure and quantify academic coursework. Here are their key purposes:\n\n1. Academic Progress\n- Track total hours of completed coursework\n- Determine progress towards degree completion\n- Measure academic load per semester\n\n2. Graduation Requirements\n- Specify minimum number of credits needed to graduate\n- Ensure students take required courses in their specific engineering discipline\n- Balance theoretical and practical coursework\n\n3. Course Weighting\n- Reflect complexity and time commitment of different courses\n- Typically based on:\n  - Lecture hours\n  - Laboratory work\n  - Project requirements\n  - Complexity of subject matter\n\n4. Course Classification\n- Distinguish between:\n  - Lower-division courses\n  - Upper-division courses\n  - Elective courses\n  - Core/mandatory courses\n\n5. Academic Standing\n- Determine full-time or part-time student status\n- Calculate grade point average (GPA)\n- Assess academic performance\n\n6. Transfer and Accreditation\n- Enable credit transfer between institutions\n- Support professional accreditation standards\n- Ensure consistent educational benchmarks\n\nCredits help standardize engineering education and provide a structured approach to academic progression.",
